{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17654157","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17654157"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:50:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:50:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18608"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18608","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18608"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.97,0,0.03,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11340"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76292"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11340","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11340"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18608"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61800"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"9936"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26304"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26308"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76292","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76292"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EPattern recognition receptors are crucial components of the innate immune system that detect potential threats to the body.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of pattern recognition receptors?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Rearrange genes to create receptor diversity","Recognise conserved molecular patterns on pathogens and damaged cells","Present peptides to T lymphocytes","Generate antibodies against specific antigens","Produce memory cells after infection"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERecognise conserved molecular patterns on pathogens and damaged cells\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary function of pattern recognition receptors (PRRs). These receptors detect pathogen-associated molecular patterns (PAMPs) such as bacterial lipopolysaccharide or viral RNA, and damage-associated molecular patterns (DAMPs) released from injured cells. This recognition triggers inflammatory responses and antimicrobial defences.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGenerate antibodies against specific antigens\u003C/strong\u003E - This is a function of B lymphocytes in adaptive immunity\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPresent peptides to T lymphocytes\u003C/strong\u003E - This is performed by antigen-presenting cells using MHC molecules\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProduce memory cells after infection\u003C/strong\u003E - Memory formation is a feature of adaptive immunity, not innate immunity\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERearrange genes to create receptor diversity\u003C/strong\u003E - Gene rearrangement occurs in T and B lymphocytes to generate diverse antigen receptors\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPattern recognition receptors are germline-encoded and recognise broad molecular patterns rather than specific antigens. They provide rapid first-line defence against infection and tissue damage.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pattern recognition receptors detect conserved molecular patterns associated with pathogens or cellular damage.","Toll-like receptors are a key family of pattern recognition receptors that recognise specific pathogen components.","Pattern recognition receptor activation triggers inflammatory responses and cytokine production."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61800"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18608"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61800","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61800"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-03T00:13:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-03T00:14:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11340"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76292"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4936","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4936"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udee1\ufe0f","name":"Immune System"